text: 9/11 Update

post_text:
The cross country team had a very successful day at yesterday's Pine City Invitational. The Jags came away winning two races individually and winning as a girls' varsity team over Pine City. Congratulations to our individual race winners Violet Cox and Reese Hartl. Reese won in 20:24, her 2nd fastest 5k as a Jaguar.

The Lady Jaguars head to head against Pine City showed that they are the current favorites in the conference. The Jags placed 1st, 4th (Raechel Painovich), 5th (Sophie Hodena), 6th (Corrina Tvedt), and 7th (Hannah Hartl) in the team standings with all five runners improving on their times from our previous race.

The JV racers also had a successful day on the course. Devon Mulder, Dalton Hosna, and Drew Churchill placed 3rd, 4th, and 5th overall while Isabella Bennett, Hallie Rootkie, and Ava Anderson placed 2nd, 3rd, and 6th in their race.

Lauren Thom and Haley Geiger also placed for the Jags finishing 3rd and 6th in the JH girls race.

HF will be continuing to provide an Activity Bus for our athletes, homework students and After School detention students. We are asking all students to sign up by NOON the day of, indicating they will be riding the activity bus. Departure time is 5:30 p.m.
1. There is no Activity Bus on Wednesdays

3. If no one has signed up for a particular route, that bus will not be available to ride at 5:30 p.m.

Dear Parents-
Here is the decision tree that the Minnesota Department of Health has put out to guide schools on making decisions about excluding staff and students to possible exposures, confirmed exposures, and symptoms. We just received this info and are still sorting through it. We wish to work with parents as partners to make decisions in the best interest of the health of our entire community. I recommend erring on the the side of caution. We are opening schools on September 8th with the goal of keeping them open. This will take effort and caution from all of us.

We look forward to seeing you all (at least virtually) next week.

JagsUnited
Rob Prater

post_text:
Hinckley Elementary School (HES) is seeking one paraprofessional position/custodian for the 2020-2021 school year. This is an up to 8 hours a day position. Responsibilities would be helping with cleaning of different areas through the school as well as helping with crowd control and supervision. The position is open until filled. Experience as a custodian or with cleaning is preferred for this position. Experience working with students is also preferred.

Application materials would include a cover letter, a resume, transcripts, and two letters of recommendation.

Please contact Bonnie Scullard, HES principal at bscullard@isd2165.org if you have additional questions or if you are interested in this position.

We have an Assistant Robotic Position open for the start of the 2020-2021 school year. This position will work directly with Joe Ranger. This position runs from January until Mid-March. Practice occurs everyday after school from 3:20 - 5:30 M-Fr and Saturday mornings. Primarily, but not limited to, the Assistant mentors will be asked to monitor student behaviors inside the metal shop and work areas, facilitate teamwork and cooperation and help transport students during competitions. Pay is based on the Schedule "C".
If you are interested, contact me via email.
Thank you.

--
Cheryl Bjerke
Dean of Students/Activities director
cbjerke@isd2165.org

post_text:
The MSHSL Board of Directors has approved the creation of an optional Fall Training Season for Volleyball, and Football, and HF's Spring sanctioned sports. These Fall Training Season are MSHSL sponsored programs.
Volleyball and Football Fall Training Seasons
.September 14th - October 3rd with 12 maximum practices.
Spring Sport Fall Training Season
.October 5th October 24 with 12 maximum practices.

This Falls Sports Season will give our students and coaches the opportunity to connect with each other and provide sport-specific training and instructions.
This Fall Sports Season will be for training purposes only, there will be no games, matches or scrimmages.
Students who participate will meet all MSHSL and school eligibility requirements including physicals and sports fees.
We will be providing an Activity Bus, however, this year we will be having a daily sign-up sheet. More information will become available from your students coach on the first day of practice.
If you have any questions, please email me at cbjerke@isd2165.org

Hinckley-Finlayson High School is looking for a 1.0 FTE Science Teacher. This position is scheduled to teach Chemistry and 8th grade Science. The ideal candidate will have experience working with students at the junior high level as well as having experience teaching Chemistry. This is a 1.0 FTE position. The ideal candidate will possess a MN secondary teaching license in 5-8 Science and Chemistry.

The posting is open until filled.
Application material would include a cover letter, a resume, transcripts, license, and 3 letters of recommendation.

Only electronic applications will be accepted. Please send application material to: bmasterson@isd2165.org

The application window to apply for Minnesota Honor Society is OPEN! HFHS students in grades 10-12 with a minimum 3.2 GPA and a history/interest in service and leadership are encouraged to apply. Find the application and read more about our organization at: https://www.hf.k12.mn.us/national-honor-society.html. Applications are due Monday, September 28.

Please contact Mrs. Alyssa Vickstrom with any questions. You can reach her at: avickstrom@isd2165.org or 320-336-0434 (Google Voice number‚Äîtext or call).

MHS is also looking for service opportunities for the coming year! Preference will be given to activities that are outdoors or in which we can practice social distancing. If you know of anyone or any events that could use cheerful volunteers, please email avickstrom@isd2165.org.

Hinckley Finlayson High School is looking for a long-term sub in the area of Social Studies. This is a 1.0 FTE and the position is teaching 7th grade US History, as well as working with junior high students who struggle with reading. A MN teaching license in social studies is required for this position. The position will begin with the start of the school year and it will last until early-October. Preference will be given to the applicant who has experience working with JH students.

This position is open until August 18th, 2020. Application materials will consist of a cover letter, resume, license, transcripts, and 3 letters of recommendations. Application materials can be emailed to HS Principal, Brian Masterson at bmasterson@isd2165.org. Only electronic submissions will be accepted.

--
Brian Masterson, Principal
Hinckley-Finlayson High School
(320) 384-6132 ext. 2505
bmasterson@isd2165.org

post_text:
The Pine County Transition Program is seeking two paraprofessionals for the 2020- 2021 school year. The duty day for these positions is 5.5 hours a day. Candidates for these positions should have strong communication skills, be willing to work collaboratively within a team, be able to think on their toes and help to develop life skills. Required qualifications for these positions include a 2-year college degree OR the ability to successfully pass the ParaPro Assessment.

Experience working with young adults with multiple needs including emotional, medical, and academic is preferred for these positions. The positions are open until July 30, 2020.

Please send application materials to Brian Masterson, HFHS principal at bmasterson@isd2165.org

Application materials consist of a cover letter, a resume, transcripts, and three letters of recommendation.

--
Brian Masterson, Principal
Hinckley-Finlayson High School
(320) 384-6132 ext. 2505
bmasterson@isd2165.org

post_text:
The Fitness Center has officially REOPENED! Per guidance we are operating at 25% capacity, which means there is a limit of 6 people in the fitness center at one time.

1. Do not enter the facility if you or anyone in your household is experiencing symptoms compatible with COVID-19. (Fever, New Cough, Shortness of breathe, new loss of taste or smell, etc.) The checklist is at the sign in area.

2. Maintaining physical distancing of 6 feet even while working out.

3. Limit items touched in the facility to only the items needed.

4. Make sure each piece of equipment used is wiped down before and after your use and dispose of the wipe accordingly.

5. Practice frequent hand washing with soap and water or use hand sanitizer. Avoid touching one‚Äôs face with unwashed hands

6. All Walking Track & Fitness Center users please sign in at the fitness center.

7. Please bring your own water bottles as the drinking fountains are closed per guidance (the water bottle filling station is available.)

post_text:
2016 Hinckley Alumni: Lexi Petite

Graduated from Gustavus Adolphus College on May 30th, 2020

Degree: B.A. in Athletic Training with a minor in Public Health and Coaching.

Current Residence: Cloverdale

Connections to H-F: Working with the summer custodial staff

What I enjoy about H-F schools: Connections still last with teachers even after graduation. Connections are important in today‚Äôs world.

Favorite memories: Trips to the river in Boxruds class, track and cross country meets, having class outside when it was nice out, and of course homecoming.

What do the students of today need to know for when they graduate?

You are guaranteed to make some mistakes. I have made my fare share of mistakes and regretting the mistake is NORMAL. You can‚Äôt go back and change the beginning (as much as we wish we could) but you can change the ending.

Fun Fact: One time I cheated on a test and still failed

Attention students going into 9th or 10th grade next year - if you're interested in a different approach to learning that is student-centered, and self-driven, consider joining EPIC (which stands for Education through Passion, Innovation and Choice). This course is completely project-based, and each project is designed by you (with help from your teachers) around your passions and interests. The course is offered as a 2 hour block, and enrollees have the option to earn both Art and English credit.

Want to know more? Check out this EPIC English Information Sheet. Contact Mrs. B Anderson or Mrs. K Hartl with any questions or to get signed up.

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1UB4dyLFx5SfKiXKcx01dtHjRdXIWnXMMVFNxv2qlyR0/edit
--
Brooke Anderson

post_text: As our school years comes to an end, we would like to recognize our last Star Student of the 2019-20 school year. Ariana Eichert is not only finishing up her distant learning experience, she is also finishing up on her elementary years at HES as she finishes up 6th grade. Ariana has been nominated at HES Star Student from Ms. Henn's 6th grade class. Ariana is a very responsible individual who really enjoys helping others. While in 6th grade Ariana was involved in various activities which she demonstrated leadership skills. Some words that describe Ariana include: kind, helpful, generous, hard worker, leader, dependable, willing, honest, creative, and caring -- just to name a few. Ariana, you will be missed by all at HES but as you move on to your jr high years, we all are confident that you will succeed as you put to use all the knowledge and skills you learned during your elementary years. Keep up the hard work Ariana - the sky's the limit!!

Teacher Appreciation Month- Thanks for all you do Mr. Letourneau

Mr. LeTourneau works hard to make sure each student is challenged, especially in math. He creates engaging lessons and his students love being in class with him. The fourth graders look forward to having him as their science teacher. He is dedicated to showing students he cares about them and their interests. He invites students to each lunch with him in his class and is often spotted throwing a football with students during recess. He even attended the 4th grade girl's basketball tournament! Mr. LeTourneau is a great teammate and teacher. HES is lucky to have a teacher like Mr. LeTourneau. Thank you for all you do!

post_text:
Teacher Appreciation Month- Thanks for all you do Mrs. Lymburner
We are so lucky to have Mrs. Lymburner. She is a very caring teacher and coworker. Her joy of teaching kindergarten and seeing how her students grow through the years is obvious. There are special memories that her former students have from being in the Clifford classroom. She shares her love of reading with students and surrounds them with a room full of fun books. Mrs. Lymburner believes it is also important to teach basic manners and how to be respectful at an early age. Those values are reflected in her own family as well.

She is a coworker that can be relied on for input, suggestions or just a shoulder to lean on. Through her years of teaching, she has acquired experience, knowledge and an endless supply of classroom materials. There have been many changes throughout her teaching career and she continues to adjust and move forward. She is always on top of accomplishing any task too. This is a great asset to the Kindergarten team! Thank you Mrs. Lymburner, for all you do!

Teacher Appreciation Month- Thanks for all you do Mr Linzmeier
Mr. Linzmeier has been a special education teacher at Hinckley Elementary for the last 6 years and is retiring at the end of this school year. Mr. L is caring, keeps things light hearted for the kids and shows excitement in their interests. He is very organized, efficient, and laid back. Mr. L is great with collaborating with others to determine what is best for our students. Although Mr. L is a Packers fan, we still love all the work he has done for the last 6 years through teaching and coaching. After retiring he can enjoy his Packers seats and go golfing daily! We will definitely be missing him next year! Thanks for everything you have done for the Hinckley-Finlayson School District!

Hinckley-Finlayson Public Schools received a mini grant in March to add a breastfeeding room to be utilized by both students and staff at Hinckley-Finlayson High School. The Grant was provided by Partners in Healthy Living, a local Statewide Health Improvement Partnership (SHIP) grantee, that supports Isanti, Kanabec, Mille Lacs and Pine County. Hinckley-Finlayson has been working with Partners in Healthy Living to work on healthy eating and active living initiatives to help improve the overall health and wellness of both our students and staff.

Finished room.....Thank you to Partners in Healthy Living.

Hinckley-Finlayson High School is looking for a 1.0 FTE Science Teacher. This position is scheduled to teach Chemistry and 8th grade Science. The ideal candidate will have experience working with students at the junior high level as well as having experience teaching Chemistry. This is a 1.0 FTE position. The ideal candidate will possess a MN secondary teaching license in 5-8 Science and Chemistry.

The posting is open until June 9th.
Application material would include a cover letter, a resume, transcripts, license, and 3 letters of recommendation.

Only electronic applications will be accepted. Please send application material to: bmasterson@isd2165.org

Katie Kreger: Teacher appreciation month (From Jay Kreger)

Besides being a fantastic spouse and mother, we at HF High are extremely fortunate to have such a dedicated and passionate teacher as Katie. Katie puts forth great effort in her lessons with her FACS students every day. Whether it be cooking, sewing, or nutrition units or helping seniors prepare for their future, she puts extreme care and thought in trying to reach and help each one of her students. She also holds students accountable and strives and encourages them to do their best. It's amazing how many different things she does for students and HF schools. Besides teaching multiple classes in FACS, she is also responsible for leading or advising FCCLA, prom, fundraiser-coordinator, the Jag store, concession stand coordinator, jr. high volleyball and keeping Mr. Kreger in line. Thanks Katie for everything you do

Mr. Lick truly has a knack for teaching! He has a great connection with his students and he makes learning fun. He is not afraid to try anything new and is always up for a challenge. Students love playing basketball with Mr. Lick at recess and sharing in his love of sports and farming. Mr. Lick is always helpful to his students but also to his coworkers. He is always willing to share his ideas and activities to ensure all 3rd graders receive fun, engaging lessons. The best part about being in Mr. Lick's class is his class pet, Penny! She is a bearded dragon that his students love dearly.

HES is lucky to have a teacher like Mr. Lick! We truly appreciate you!!

post_text: Joe Ranger makes teaching an art. Whether it is shooting t-shirts at (or over) the football stands, building a robot controlled by a video game joystick controller, or showing off his vapor cannon inside his classroom by firing clouds of fog across the room, he always keeps students guessing. During my first year of teaching, he told me about how his goal is not to make his class good but to make it actively awesome. I can see that awesomeness throughout the year as duct tape canoes, hydraulic backhoes, and self-loading marble rollercoasters come out of his classroom, carried by students, grinning because most teachers would not let you try to paddle across the swimming pool in a homemade duct tape boat. I am privileged to have such a creative and kind mentor. Thank you for all you do, Ranger

post_text:
Teacher Appreciation Month-Mr. Kelash

Chris Kelash is a quality educator at Finlayson Elementary School. He is a thoughtful, considerate teacher who takes the time to get to know all of his students. His students love being a part of his classroom and getting to know him, too. Chris always ensures everyone is mastering the standards, and he is constantly learning and using best practices to motivate students to succeed and grow academically, socially, and emotionally. His coworkers can always count on him to help out with whatever needs they have in their classrooms as well. Mr. Kelash is a caring, positive role model that makes our school a better place; the students and staff at FES are lucky to have him.

We (baseball and softball) will be selling our annual Jaguar Coupon card starting this week and for the next several weeks.

The Jaguar coupon card is now available for purchase at a cost of $20. The cards can be purchased at the High School main office during normal business hours. Cards can also be purchased from baseball and softball players by contacting them with your order request. Thanks for supporting our teams and local businesses during this time.

Teacher Appreciation Month - Mr Vickstrom
Video from Alyssa Vickstrom

From Emily Klar:

Mr. V aka APUSH god. AP U.S History is tough, I‚Äôve heard seniors say that it is the hardest AP class they have ever taken. With distance learning that makes APUSH so much harder. That never stopped Mr. V though, he has done all he can possibly do to make sure we as APUSH students will pass our test. He never gives us more than we can chew. I am very appreciative of his efforts to keep in touch with us and is always there to answer any questions we have. I can say this with 100% certainty that the students to take APUSH after me will be lucky to have Mr. V (APUSH god) as their instructor. Thank you, Mr. V.
